important in geometry where our natural intuition&nbsp;
often tempts us to forgo proper definitions today&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:27.760
we're going to talk about a subject which often&nbsp;
isn't pinned down very precisely in elementary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:33.920
courses how to define quadrilaterals&nbsp;
quadrangles and more generally n-gons&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:38.800
so let me remind you that we're talking&nbsp;
just about basic elementary geometry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:43.440
everything built up over the rational&nbsp;
numbers and we have been talking about points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.440 --> 00:00:49.360
so a point for us is just an ordered pair of&nbsp;
numbers say x y and we've been talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:58.640
lines for us a line is a triple a to b to c&nbsp;
a proportion enclosed in pointy brackets and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:58.640 --> 00:01:02.880
we have a relation of incidence between points&nbsp;
and lines in terms of this equation here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:09.280
and we talked last time about the definition of&nbsp;
a triangle this is just one of several possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.280 --> 00:01:14.720
definitions but it's a very convenient one for&nbsp;
us a set of three non-linear points is what a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:22.560
triangle actually is so here's points a b and c&nbsp;
they are not collinear in other words they do not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:29.360
all lie on a straight line and so they define a&nbsp;
triangle and precisely it means that the triangle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:36.240
is actually a set so it's a set containing three&nbsp;
objects the three objects are these three points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.520 --> 00:01:42.320
so if you want to look at it more carefully&nbsp;
each one of these points would actually be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:49.600
an ordered pair enclosed in square brackets just&nbsp;
like that and i remind you that the set notation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.600 --> 00:01:54.400
means that the order in which we write these three&nbsp;
points doesn't matter so this set is also the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.400 --> 00:02:04.560
as the set b c a or b a c and here's our notation&nbsp;
for the triangle abc just the three points with a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:11.280
bar over it to denote the triangle and i just make&nbsp;
sure that we understand that if you have three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:18.560
collinear points like these points d e&nbsp;
and f then this set is not a triangle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.560 --> 00:02:23.920
it does contain three points it isn't a set but&nbsp;
the three points are cleaner so technically it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:32.240
not a triangle all right so with those foundations&nbsp;
now let's ask how do we define a quadrilateral the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:39.760
analogous object with four points instead of three&nbsp;
when it comes to quadrilaterals it's tempting to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:39.760 --> 00:02:45.280
just use a picture to write down something&nbsp;
like this and say well there's a quadrilateral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:52.880
a b c d but we want a more precise definition and&nbsp;
here is one way of proceeding so let's have a good&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:58.800
look at this definition of a quadrilateral&nbsp;
we say that a b c d with a bar over it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:07.680
is a quadrilateral means it is a list a b c d of&nbsp;
distinct points so there are four points in a list&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:17.600
no three which are collinear with the&nbsp;
further convention that a b c d that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:24.480
quadrilateral formed from four points in that&nbsp;
order is the same as the quadrilateral b c d a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.720
and also that a b c d is the same as a d c b so&nbsp;
let's have a look at what the definition means

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:44.720
first of all we have four points and we have&nbsp;
a list this is different from a set in a list&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:50.400
the order matters there's a first element&nbsp;
a second element a third element a fourth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:55.280
element in this case so in a list we are not&nbsp;
allowed to change things around like that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.840 --> 00:04:00.560
okay and we're insisting that no three of these&nbsp;
points are collinear that's clear enough and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:07.360
what's the significance of these two conventions&nbsp;
the convention is here that we are allowed to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:14.400
rotate our list so if one person says oh this&nbsp;
is a b c d another person could come along and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:19.680
say no this is the quadrilateral b c d a and&nbsp;
it would mean exactly the same quadrilateral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:25.200
so in other words which of the points&nbsp;
we're starting with in our listing of them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:32.320
doesn't matter the cyclical order does and this&nbsp;
rule captures that property we're allowed to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:37.840
rotate the a from the beginning to the end and of&nbsp;
course you're allowed to do it again so you could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:45.920
rotate that b around to the other side so the&nbsp;
same quadrilateral would be c d a b now what's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:50.960
meaning of this convention it means that you're&nbsp;
allowed to go in the opposite order and you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:57.200
the same quadrilateral so not only are we allowed&nbsp;
to start every anywhere we want to but we're also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:03.200
allowed to go in either direction this way or&nbsp;
this way when we're listing those four points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.720 --> 00:05:11.920
this makes it very clear what exactly a&nbsp;
quadrilateral is and let's note that abcd&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:21.440
that quadrilateral is not equal to abdc so abcd&nbsp;
that's one quadrilateral a b d c in that order&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:28.960
that is a different quadrilateral okay&nbsp;
here are some additional conventions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:35.920
about the quadrilateral abcd that we're&nbsp;
talking about here we say that the points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:42.960
of the quadrilateral are exactly these four a&nbsp;
b c d those are the points of the quadrilateral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:52.480
we say that the lines of the quadrilateral&nbsp;
are these four lines a b b c c cd and da&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:58.960
the other two possible lines that you could&nbsp;
create these ones here we call them diagonal lines&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:00.800 --> 00:06:06.480
so they're separate from lines they have a&nbsp;
different relationship to the quadrilateral&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.440
in projective geometry which is&nbsp;
something we haven't introduced yet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:17.600
there is a complete symmetry between points and&nbsp;
lines that's not the case of euclidean geometry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:22.800
but in projective geometry it becomes very&nbsp;
interesting to talk also about quadrangles which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:29.840
is basically exactly the same kind of definition&nbsp;
but we replace points and lines and lines with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:36.880
points throughout but for elementary geometry the&nbsp;
notion of a quadrangle is really superfluous it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:43.520
really not needed the quadrilateral suffices&nbsp;
for most purposes let's have a look at how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.520 --> 00:06:48.400
we generalize the notion of quadrilateral&nbsp;
to an n-gon like a pentagon or a hexagon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.200 --> 00:06:55.840
so what is an n gone we choose an n a natural&nbsp;
number bigger than or equal to three to start with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.880 --> 00:07:02.560
and then we say that an n gone labeled&nbsp;
a1 a2 up to a n with a bar over it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:10.400
is by definition a list it's a list&nbsp;
a 1 a 2 up to a n of distinct points

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:19.440
with some conventions first of all&nbsp;
you're allowed to rotate the first point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.640
to the end and you have the same end gun

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:32.080
and you're allowed to go through those endpoints&nbsp;
in the opposite order instead of a1 a2 up to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:39.920
n you're allowed to say a n a n minus 1 through&nbsp;
to a1 so those two ways of ordering are the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:46.320
and finally we agree that no three&nbsp;
consecutive points are collinear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:56.880
so for example here's a five gun a1 a2 a3 a4&nbsp;
a5 it happens to be non-convex that's all right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.880 --> 00:08:08.160
so that end gone would be the same as the&nbsp;
end gone a2 a3 a4 a5 a1 or a2 a1 a5 a4 a3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:16.720
and the condition is that no three consecutive&nbsp;
points are collinear so a1 a2 a3 they're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:23.360
consecutive or a4 a5 a1 they're also consecutive&nbsp;
and no three consecutive points are collinear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:34.880
here's a 6-gon which is also non-convex a1 a2&nbsp;
a3a4a5a6 now we have some collinear points or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:39.840
almost linear those three points might be linear&nbsp;
but they're not consecutive so it still counts as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.560 --> 00:08:47.520
an n-gone here's another six gone&nbsp;
one two three four five six points&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:56.320
this one here happens to be convex of course the&nbsp;
theory of n-gons in general is rather complicated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.320 --> 00:09:03.360
even quadrilaterals form a rather rich subject&nbsp;
for investigation but i wanted today just to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:09.920
clarify the idea that it's important in&nbsp;
